                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d345">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">765.84/4590: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister Resident in Ethiopia</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Engert</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Addis Ababa</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-06-06T14:00:00+03:00"
                            >June 6, 1936—2 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 7:20 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>398. Department’s 256, May 29, 5 p.m. Question was discussed at the regular
                    meeting of the Diplomatic Corps this morning. British and French Ambassadors in
                    Rome having protested against the decree they were assured that authorities here
                    would be instructed not to enforce it as regards foreigners. This appears to
                    have been done for although the decree has not been repealed or modified no
                    attempt has been made to apply its provisions to foreigners.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Engert</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
